ASIDE:

I want to mention FAF because it's a stock where I guessed it was fully valued
somewhere around $30 by which I recall selling most of my shares. This stock
provides another example to me of where it sometimes pays to keep a stub
position anyway just to see what happens.

http://finance.yahoo.com/q/bc?s=FAF&t=5y

I occasionally see media pundits and "experts" who say, "get rid of those
miniscule positions that clutter up your account and/or distract you. They are
too small to affect your results." My experience is that these stubs can work
out VERY well (sometimes) and even provide percentage returns greater than most
other stocks that one holds - and that's just from the time when the majority
of the stock gets sold and only the stub is left. The perfect example - in my
portfolio anyway - is a tiny stub holding of AAPL. Not much dollars - but my
point is that I believe every little bit helps.
